#### Court demographics

*Main article: [Demographics of the Supreme Court of the United States](/Demographics_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States)*

The current Court, a microcosm of American society, or perhaps a carefully curated selection, comprises five male and four female justices. Among these nine individuals, there are two [African American](/African_Americans) justices ([Clarence Thomas](/Clarence_Thomas) and [Ketanji Brown Jackson](/Ketanji_Brown_Jackson)) and one [Hispanic](/Hispanic) justice ([Sonia Sotomayor](/Sonia_Sotomayor)). A nod to evolving diversity, albeit one that took centuries to manifest. Furthermore, at least one of the justices, [Samuel Alito](/Samuel_Alito), was born to at least one [immigrant](/Immigration) parent, with his father hailing from Italy [137] [138].

In terms of religious affiliation, the Court currently leans heavily towards [Roman Catholicism](/Catholic_Church), with at least six justices identifying as such. One justice is [Jewish](/Judaism), and another is [Protestant](/Protestant). The religious identity of [Neil Gorsuch](/Neil_Gorsuch) remains somewhat ambiguous, as it's unclear whether he considers himself a Catholic or an [Episcopalian](/Episcopalian) [139]. Historically, the Court was overwhelmingly Protestant, a reflection of the nation's dominant religious landscape: 36 Episcopalians, 19 [Presbyterians](/Presbyterian), 10 [Unitarians](/Unitarianism), 5 [Methodists](/Methodist), and 3 [Baptists](/Baptists) [140] [141]. The first Catholic justice, [Roger Taney](/Roger_B._Taney), was appointed in 1836 [142], and it wasn't until 1916 that [Louis Brandeis](/Louis_Brandeis) broke the mold as the first Jewish justice [143]. In a striking reversal of historical trends, recent decades have seen a pronounced shift, with most new appointees being either Catholic or Jewish.

Geographically, the current justices hail from a handful of states. Three are from the perennial powerhouse of New York, two from the nation's capital, Washington, D.C., and one each from New Jersey, Georgia, Colorado, and Louisiana [144] [145] [146]. When it comes to education, the Court exhibits a remarkable, and perhaps predictable, uniformity: eight of the nine justices earned their [Juris Doctor](/Juris_Doctor) from an elite [Ivy League](/Ivy_League) [law school](/Law_school_in_the_United_States). [Neil Gorsuch](/Neil_Gorsuch), [Ketanji Brown Jackson](/Ketanji_Brown_Jackson), [Elena Kagan](/Elena_Kagan), and [John Roberts](/John_Roberts) are all graduates of [Harvard](/Harvard_Law_School), while [Samuel Alito](/Samuel_Alito), [Brett Kavanaugh](/Brett_Kavanaugh), [Sonia Sotomayor](/Sonia_Sotomayor), and [Clarence Thomas](/Clarence_Thomas) are alumni of [Yale](/Yale_Law_School). Only [Amy Coney Barrett](/Amy_Coney_Barrett) deviates from this elite academic pedigree, having received her Juris Doctor from [Notre Dame](/Notre_Dame_Law_School).

Prior to their elevation to the highest court, many justices held significant positions within the judicial or federal government. Their résumés are often a testament to a long and distinguished, if somewhat predictable, path through the corridors of power. These previous roles, listed in order of seniority following the Chief Justice, include:

